-- PRESS DIGEST- Wall Street Journal - Oct 15
-- 
-- Wed Oct 15, 2014 12:57AM EDT
-- None



Oct 15 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Wall Street Journal. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

* Oil prices posted their biggest one-day drop in nearly two years Tuesday as a U.S.-led wave of crude has crashed into weak global demand, threatening the stability of some countries and providing an economic lifeline to others. (http://on.wsj.com/1z9dgX4)  * A clinic in the Liberian capital Monrovia has hired seven Ebola survivors to counsel other patients suffering from the virus. (http://on.wsj.com/1tstCaS)  * AbbVie Inc <ABBV.N> has notified Shire Plc <SHP.L> that its board intends to reconsider its recommendation that AbbVie shareholders adopt the companies' merger agreement. (http://on.wsj.com/ZYBPXv)  * JP Morgan <JPM.N> and Citigroup <C.N> each said they socked away hundreds of millions of dollars in the third quarter to cover legal costs, a sobering reminder that they are still reckoning with crisis-era behavior that has triggered billions in penalties already. (http://on.wsj.com/11k68Il)  * After a false start that set back its plans at least two years, Hilton Worldwide Holdings <HLT.N> is launching a boutique-hotel chain that aims for a wider audience and lower room rates than some direct competitors. (http://on.wsj.com/1w1DFBn)